  <body>
    <main>
      <header class="hero">
        <h1>How to read the analysis</h1>
        <p class="tagline">What the sidebar is telling you — and what it isn't.</p>
        <div class="cta-row">
          <a href="/" class="cta primary">Open the editor →</a>
          <a href="/paste" class="cta secondary">Paste-and-analyze</a>
        </div>
      </header>

      <section>
        <p>
          Folio describes your manuscript. It never grades you. Every number in the sidebar is a
          measurement against the <em>age band you chose</em> — change the band and the same text
          reads differently, because the reader changed, not the writing.
        </p>
        <p>
          Where a metric rests on published research, the source is named below. Where it's a
          working convention of the engine, we say that too. The sections follow the sidebar,
          top to bottom.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Length</h2>
        <p>
          Word count, measured against the publishing conventions for your band
          (SCBWI guidance; Mary Kole's length guidelines):
        </p>
        <table class="bands">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Band</th><th>Ages</th><th>Words</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Board</td><td>0–3</td><td>up to 100</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Early picture</td><td>0–3</td><td>up to 400</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Picture</td><td>3–7</td><td>up to 600</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Early reader</td><td>5–9</td><td>1,000–2,500</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Chapter</td><td>7–10</td><td>5,000–10,000</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>
          Sentence counts use real segmentation — <em>"Now run along," said Mrs. Rabbit.</em> is
          one sentence, despite the period in <em>Mrs.</em> — and average sentence length tracks
          the breath of your prose read aloud.
        </p>
        <p class="use">Targets are conventions, not laws. But editors feel them, and the youngest readers feel them most.</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Vocabulary</h2>
        <h3>Familiar words (Tier 1)</h3>
        <p>
          The share of your words a young reader is likely to already know — measured against the
          Dale–Chall familiar-word list (words roughly 80% of fourth-graders recognize in print)
          plus the Dolch and Fry sight words. This is the broad "how much of this is already known"
          number. A note on calibration: the list is normed at the top of our age range, so it's
          most discriminating for early-reader and chapter texts and naturally sits near 100% for
          board books.
        </p>
        <h3>Sight-word coverage</h3>
        <p>
          A narrower measure: the share of your words on the Dolch and Fry lists specifically — the
          high-frequency words beginning readers learn to recognize whole, without sounding out.
          High coverage means an early reader moves through your text on recognition; lower coverage
          shifts the work to decoding.
        </p>
        <h3>Unique words &amp; type-token ratio</h3>
        <p>
          Unique words divided by total words. In a board book, a <em>low</em> ratio is usually
          craft — repetition is how the youngest readers participate. In a chapter opening, a
          higher ratio is normal. There is no good score; there is only the question of whether
          the repetition you see is the repetition you meant.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Reach words</h2>
        <p>
          Words likely to sit just past your target reader's current mastery — flagged because they
          fall outside the familiar Tier-1 core (the Dale–Chall list plus sight words). In the editor
          they underline where they live, and the sidebar attributes each one to the spread where it
          first appears, so you can see clustering at a glance.
        </p>
        <p>
          Some reach words are the point. The zone just past mastery is where vocabulary grows —
          educators call it the zone of proximal development (Vygotsky) — and shared reading is how
          children cross it. A handful per spread invites growth. A pile-up on one spread turns
          reading into work.
        </p>
        <p class="use">One honest limit: a character's name and an inflected form like "bunnies" both read as reach words, and the tool doesn't yet separate a rich literary word ("mischief") from a genuinely rare one ("sirrah"). Trust your eye over the count.</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Phonology</h2>
        <h3>Decodability</h3>
        <p>
          A 0–1 estimate of how kindly your text treats an emerging reader who is sounding words
          out. It weights how early each speech sound is typically mastered (consonant norms from
          Crowe &amp; McLeod, 2020 — the research base SLPs already use) and how complex each
          syllable's shape is. The exact weighting is an engine convention, documented in the
          source.
        </p>
        <h3>Syllables</h3>
        <p>
          Average syllables per word, plus the shapes: <code>CV</code> ("go") and
          <code>CVC</code> ("cat") are the friendly ones; consonant clusters
          (<code>CCVC</code>, "stop") arrive later in development.
        </p>
        <h3>Phoneme inventory</h3>
        <p>
          Every speech sound your manuscript uses, grouped by the age most children produce it
          accurately — later-acquired sounds (<em>r</em>, <em>th</em>) tint warmer. Click any
          phoneme to light up every word containing it, in place. Useful for spotting a sound your
          text leans on, or for matching a text to a child's current inventory.
        </p>
        <h3>Guessed pronunciations</h3>
        <div class="honesty-card">
          <p>
            Folio's pronouncing dictionary covers the core early-reading vocabulary. Anything
            outside it — invented names, rare words — gets an <em>estimated</em> pronunciation,
            and this list names those words. It's the engine being honest: phoneme and meter
            readings for these words rest on guesses. If your manuscript stars a Snorfblat,
            weigh the phonology numbers accordingly.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Prosody</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Dominant meter</strong> is the stress pattern your lines lean toward: iambic
          (da-DUM), trochaic (DUM-da), anapestic (da-da-DUM), dactylic (DUM-da-da).
          <strong>Meter consistency</strong> is how much of the text fits that pattern, and the
          <strong>rhyme scheme</strong> letters (AABB, ABAB) mark which line endings rhyme.
        </p>
        <p>
          Prose reads "—" or "mixed", and that is not a defect — most picture books aren't metered.
          Verse with a deliberately loose beat reads "mixed" too, and so can verse built on words
          the dictionary had to guess. Lines are read the way you broke them: the meter starts
          fresh on each line, and an unstressed pickup syllable before a line's first beat is
          understood, not penalized.
        </p>
        <p class="use">If you write metered verse, watch consistency while you revise — a dip often points at the exact line where the beat stumbles.</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Per spread</h2>
        <p>
          The pacing strip. Each bar is one spread's word count against a soft ceiling — the
          manuscript target spread across your non-wordless spreads, with headroom. The ceiling is
          a documented heuristic, not a rule: picture books distribute words unevenly on purpose.
          The strip exists so the unevenness is a choice you can see.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Warnings</h2>
        <p>
          Folio currently warns about two things: total word count over your band's maximum, and
          under its minimum where one exists. "Info" severity means <em>noted</em>, not
          <em>fix it</em>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>What Folio doesn't do</h2>
        <p>
          It doesn't score you, rank you, or compare you to anyone. It will never write or rewrite
          your text — not a word. And your manuscript never leaves your browser: analysis runs
          locally, drafts save to your device, and there's no account and no server.
        </p>
      </section>

